Ron? MR. MILBERG: Okay.
Thank you, Mike.
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
Today I'll provide some background on the IFA program and then talk about how it's evolved over the years and then finally discuss today's situation.
To begin with, the imported fire ant, or IFA, were introduced into the southern United States 60 to 80 years ago.
After the ants were first observed around 1920, landowners in infested areas began applying available
14 15 16 17 18 19
insecticides, such as calcium cyanide dust.
With the advent of chlorinated hydrocarbons to cost-effectively control the ants, a federal quarantine was established in 1958.
The quarantine currently regulates all or portions of Alabama, Arkansas, California, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, New Mexico, North Carolina,
20 21 22 23 24 25
Oklahoma, Puerto Rico, South Carolina, Tennessee, and Texas.
The federal quarantine regulates the movement of articles known to spread IFA, including nursery stock and soil.
The original program was a cooperative effort between APHIS and the states in three areas, including detection, to find and eradicate isolated infestations;
7 1 2 3 4 5 6 regulatory activity, to slow IFA's spread by controlling the movement of regulated articles; and finally, control, to reduce to reduce populations, using wide-area pesticide applications.
As registrations and food tolerances for chlorinated hydrocarbons were canceled during the 1960s and
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
1970s, wide-area pesticide applications were no longer practical due to the poor efficacy of available pesticides.
The IFA program then shifted to baits and organophosphates.
Unfortunately, some of these compounds, such as chlorpyrifos, were less effective than previously used materials.
During the 1980s, with the continued loss of
14 15 16 17 18 19
chemicals, the federal program focused on methods development, primarily testing of new materials to certify regulated articles for interstate movement.
During the 1990s, appropriations for many federal domestic programs declined or were capped, and states assumed more IFA survey and regulatory responsibility.
Such
20 21 22 23 24 25
state activities were conducted, in part, using cooperative funding agreements with APHIS.
Most federal dollars were passed through to the states to ensure compliance with the federal quarantine.
I'll put up a graph here that shows funding over the last 10 years or so, and as shown on this graph, the
8 1 2 3 4 5 6 continued pressure on domestic budgets caused funding for the IFA program to decline from about $5 million in 1990 to $100,000 in 2000.
Of this year's $100,000 appropriation, Congress earmarked 58,000 for IFA work in New Mexico.
And given the current funding level, essentially no dollars are available for pass-through to the other states.
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
Despite the low funding level, APHIS continues to maintain the federal quarantine by annually updating the list of infested areas contained in the Federal Register.
In addition, our Investigative and Enforcement Services staff looks into about 10 to 20 quarantine violations annually.
About a third of these cases are closed with
14 15 16 17 18 19
warnings issued by the local plant protection and quarantine officer for a first-time violation.
Another third are closed with no action if the shipping facility was under a compliance agreement and treatments were applied in accordance with that agreement.
The last third are assessed civil penalties in accordance with the law.
These normally
20 21 22 23 24 25
range up to $1,000 per violation, which is the maximum allowed by statute.
The typical fine ranges from $500 to $2,000, depending on the severity of the violation and the number of -- number we can charge.
In addition to our IES activity, APHIS continues to focus on development of new regulatory treatments and
9 1 2 3 4 5 6 nursery compliance protocols.
About $350,000 is allocated annually to Gulfport, Mississippi, for methods development work.
To our knowledge, Gulfport is the only facility in the country that is developing IFA regulatory treatments.
So, given the above developments, we decided to hold public meetings and to get input on what direction the
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
IFA program should take.
To help stimulate discussion on this issue, we proposed the three options shown.
Under option one, we would maintain our imported fire ant program with minimal regulatory activity, in line with current funding.
This option would provide uniform standards and consistent interstate shipping requirements for the regulated industry.
Under this option, with the current
14 15 16 17 18 19
funding level, most states would enforce the federal quarantine without federal dollars.
Under option two, we would eliminate the federal quarantine and develop model guidelines for states to use in harmonizing their quarantines.
This option would reduce federal costs and may provide uniformity without federal
20 21 22 23 24 25
regulation.
However, under this option, states may impose more or less stringent requirements, and these requirements could differ from state to state.
Under option three, we would eliminate the IFA regulations and would participate in establishing a voluntary nursery compliance program.
This option would
10 1 2 3 4 5 6 also reduce federal costs and may provide uniformity without federal regulation.
However, such a certification program is not mandatory and could result in less than 100 percent participation.
At this time, the agency has made no decision on how to proceed.
All options, including any submitted in
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
writing or presented at this meeting, will be considered before a final decision is proposed.
Thank you again for your interest, and that concludes my briefing.
MR. LIDSKY: Okay.
I'm going to call our first registered speaker, and that is Mr. Benny Graves, please.
MR. GRAVES: It's good to be with you today.
I'm
14 15 16 17 18 19
Benny Graves.
I represent the Mississippi Department of Agriculture Bureau of Plant Industry and I'd like to read a few comments from the Mississippi Department of Agriculture concerning this issue.
"We are glad to have this opportunity to comment on the course of action USDA-APHIS should take in dealing
20 21 22 23 24 25
with the federal fire ant quarantine.
The Mississippi Department of Agriculture Bureau of Plant Industry believes that USDA-APHIS should maintain the imported fire ant quarantine.
Keeping the federal fire ant quarantine in place is of vital importance to our nursery and beekeeping industries.
Both of these agricultural industries ship into
11 1 2 3 4 5 6 uninfested states.
Because of the USDA-APHIS involvement in the fire ant quarantine, there is a uniform, consistent set of rules for our nurseries and beekeepers to follow when shipping into uninfested states.
We do not want to see the federal fire ant quarantine replaced with state-by-state fire ant rules governing how a crop must be grown, shipped,
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
or treated.
Such regulatory action at the state level would create a regulatory nightmare for the affected industries in our state.
"Mississippi currently has 117 nurseries and nursery dealers and 20 beekeepers who would be immediately impacted by any change in the federal fire ant quarantine.
"Beyond these two industries, the Mississippi
14 15 16 17 18 19
Department of Agriculture believes the USDA-APHIS should be involved because of the national threat fire ants pose as an invasive species.
Fire ants have a negative impact on both public health and environment whenever they become established.
This threat should be taken seriously at the federal level.
The minimum action level should be the
20 21 22 23 24 25
continuation of the federal fire ant quarantine."
In addition to that, of course, Mississippi would support any funding mechanism to increase funding on the federal fire ant program.
"In conclusion, the Mississippi Bureau of Plant Industry thanks the USDA-APHIS for the opportunity to make
12 1 2 3 4 5 6 this public comment."
