Mr. Eddy Edmondson, please.
MR. EDMONDSON: Good morning.
I'm Eddy Edmondson.
I'm the president and CEO of the Texas Nursery and Landscape Association.
The Texas Nursery and Landscape
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
Association, hereafter referred to as TNLA, is a trade organization that represents all segments of the nursery and the landscape industry in Texas, being the wholesale production, retail, landscape, and allied businesses.
The sales volume of the nursery and landscape products and services in Texas is in excess of $14 billion annually.
My comments are made on behalf of our members.
14 15 16 17 18 19
In addition to those members who are present here today, there are over 1,000 growers in Texas alone who are affected by this quarantine.
Unfortunately, this hearing is taking place during the busiest time of the year for growers, which is the spring shipping season, and only a few can be present today to testify.
We have received copies of letters from a
20 21 22 23 24 25
large number of growers who will be submitting written comments.
Both our industry and our state have felt the sting of the imported fire ant issue personally and in our pocketbooks for over 20 years.
The nursery and landscape industry has willingly assumed a portion of the financial
13 1 2 3 4 5 6 burden for slowing the spread of this agricultural and health menace across the United States.
Since the imported fire ant problem has been around for many years, it is possible that during the USDAAPHIS budget development process, it suffered from being a longstanding issue, losing the impetus of being a "hot
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
issue."
We welcome this opportunity to inform decisionmakers about the impact of losing funding for the imported fire ant quarantine.
One reason that past efforts to control the spread of the imported fire ant have experienced some success has been the implementation of a single quarantine standard across the country.
The quarantine has not been
14 15 16 17 18 19
abused as a means of regionalism or as a protectionist ploy, because all states were playing under the same rules enforced by the federal quarantine.
The value of a united effort is further illustrated by the Texas Imported Fire Ant Research and Management Plan adopted by the 74th Texas Legislature.
This
20 21 22 23 24 25
plan includes research, education, quarantine and survey projects, and community-wide management efforts.
The lead agency is the Texas Agricultural Extension Service, with cooperation among the Texas A
14 1 2 3 4 5 6 In 1998, this project produced a regional publication for Alabama, Arkansas, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas, prepared by Drs. Bastiaan Drees and Charles Barr of the Texas A
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
Georgia.
We have seen positive results from the Fire Ant Management Plan after only a few years.
The national effort would do well to use the philosophy of this program as a model and focus on a unified research and implementation approach rather than creating an environment in which each state may go its own way.
The imported fire ant issue is not just a nursery and landscape
14 15 16 17 18 19
issue, not just an agricultural issue.
It is a health and human safety issue, and as such, it is worthy of the attention of the federal government.
However, the very nature of the problem presents a threat to our industry.
Imagine for a moment that the states not yet infested decided it was in the interest of
20 21 22 23 24 25
their citizens to cut off all imports of plant material in soil from the quarantined states.
Availability of plant material to the nursery and landscape markets in the uninfested areas would be affected, because most of the major growing areas of the United States are in the quarantined states.
The economy of the quarantined states
15 1 2 3 4 5 6 would be affected, because the nursery and landscape industry is a significant economic factor in these states.
Scientists tell us that it is not possible to completely contain the spread of the imported fire ant.
Therefore, we contend that the best strategy is to slow the spread of this pest down with proven techniques that do not
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
disrupt the economies of the areas involved.
Another issue affected by the quarantine is fair competition in the marketplace.
A uniform quarantine with adequate funding to state departments of agriculture for surveys and enforcement helps ensure that law-abiding businesses are not at an unfair competitive disadvantage.
In the interest of economic health, human health
14 15 16 17 18 19
and safety, and marketplace equity, the Texas Nursery and Landscape Association strongly urges restoration of $7.5 million in funding for the USDA-APHIS imported fire ant line item.
Our organization is available to provide information and background on this issue at any time, and if
20 21 22 23 24 25
any of you have any questions today, I'll be glad to address them.
MR. LIDSKY: Thank you very much.
Mr. Craig Albiston, please.
MR. ALBISTON: Turkey Creek Farms appreciates the opportunity to comment at this public hearing.
We strongly
16 1 2 3 4 5 6 urge that the federal fire ant quarantine be maintained and that funding be restored to combat this destructive and invasive pest.
Red imported fire ants were accidentally introduced into the United States near Mobile, Alabama, in the early 1900s.
This invasive pest has spread throughout
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
the Southeast, from eastern North Carolina, south to Florida, and west through much of Texas.
The USDA's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service, otherwise known as APHIS, maintains a quarantine to slow the spread into uninfested areas.
The quarantine includes rules for shipping fire-ant-free nursery and greenhouse plants.
Quarantine activities, such as infestation surveys,
14 15 16 17 18 19
compliance monitoring and enforcement are shared by APHIS and the states.
The partnership between the federal government and state governments has worked well on this issue.
Federal funding has been virtually eliminated for fiscal year 2000.
With no funding, the states and affected
20 21 22 23 24 25
industries will be burdened to finance this quarantine.
Some have even spoken about rescinding the federal quarantine altogether.
This would not be good.
Imported fire ants pose a danger to human health, to our agriculture, and to our property.
According to a Texas A
17 1 2 3 4 5 6 September 19, 1999, "The red imported fire ant is digging deep into the wallets of Texans.
Damage and management of the imported pest in the five major urban areas of Texas cost more than $580 million in 1998."
There are huge areas of the United States which are still uninfested.
They want to stay free from this pest as long as possible.
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
The American nursery industry is the most promising growth segment in American agriculture.
The majority of us are small businesses and family farms, and since both field-grown and containerized nursery stock are regulated under the federal quarantine, we bear considerable costs to comply with the quarantine requirements.
We have been and are willing to share the burden of controlling the
14 15 16 17 18 19
pest.
Turkey Creek Farms is the largest containergrowing operation in Harris County, Texas.
Our 160-acre nursery is located in northern Harris County, near Houston's Bush Intercontinental Airport.
We grow a diverse assortment of trees, shrubs, and color plants in containers ranging
20 21 22 23 24 25
from 4 inch to 15 gallons.
And while greenhouse and bedding plants account for about 60 percent of our annual sales, about 90 percent of our acreage in production is devoted to trees and shrubs.
Our pest management practices include baiting, scouting for pests, and periodic spot treatments, all done
18 1 2 3 4 5 6 with the aim of diligently working to grow superior quality, pest-free products that our customers demand.
On September 23, 1994, Fireban, a synthetic pyrethroid, was approved by APHIS for the imported fire ant quarantine program and imported fire-ant-free nursery program.
We use Fireban in our soil mix.
Twice a year, we
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
bait with Logic, and we spot-treat with Orthene, Diazinon, and Dursban.
Inspectors from the Texas Department of Agriculture routinely visit us to ensure our compliance to the federal fire ant quarantine in addition to monitoring our pest eradication efforts.
Depending on their size, individual nurseries are
14 15 16 17 18 19
likely spending anywhere from a few thousand to several hundred thousand dollars a year on fire ants.
Our annual expenses at Turkey Creek Farms are about $58,200.
They are broken down as follows: labor cost for baiting and pesticide applications, $6,200; administrative costs, management expenses, $3,000; soil amendment, $46,400;
20 21 22 23 24 25
baiting with Logic, $600; and the pesticide spot treatments, $2,000.
Turkey Creek Farms ships to customers in Oklahoma, Louisiana, Arkansas, Alabama, Mississippi, Missouri, and Tennessee.
If the states are left alone to fund and erect their own quarantine regulations, nursery
19 1 2 3 4 5 6 producers like ourselves will be faced with multiple standards for the products we grow and ship.
Furthermore, adequate enforcement is needed to ensure that law-abiding businesses are not put at an unfair competitive disadvantage in the marketplace.
This can only happen through an adequately funded federal quarantine.
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
While we may never be able to eradicate fire ants, the federal quarantine that is being administered by the states' departments of agriculture are working to slow the advance into uninfested areas, while pesticides and better management techniques work to reduce the widespread damage of these pests.
Universities, like Texas A
14 15 16 17 18 19
and better controls, and chemical manufacturers are bringing new pest management tools on line.
Because fire ants are both an invasive species and a human health threat, preventing their spread is a legitimate public goal and a reasonable expenditure of public funds.
While there is a need for partnership between
20 21 22 23 24 25
the federal government and state governments, the federal government, through APHIS, is best equipped to deal with the fire ant issue.
We urge those of you here today to support the restoration of the $7.5 million in funding for the USDAAPHIS fire ant line item in order to ensure a viable and effective quarantine.
