And I want to tell you, I've got some bird dogs that are probably going to die of old age before they see a native covey of quail in my county.
These fire ants, when the baby quail hatch out, they devour them.
The ones that
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
live, the fire ants eat up the small insects that they need for food to survive.
So they have really decimated the quail population in my county and several surrounding counties.
I live up in north central Texas.
My other hobby I mentioned was trout fishing.
There's not that many trout fisheries in the state of Texas, but the best one we have is not far from here, down on the
14 15 16 17 18 19
Guadalupe River.
Trout love ants.
They get fat on ants.
They're almost pure protein.
And the last spring, the fire ants in that Guadalupe watershed begin to mate, and they fly up and, most of you know, they come back down.
Well, numerous ants landed in the river, and the fish ingested those ants.
Well, the venom in the fire ant is toxic.
And
20 21 22 23 24 25
those fire ants killed 23,000 rainbow trout and ruined my fishing! They got my quail, and now they've got my fish! So, you know, I'm ticked off.
I don't think we've had a pest of this magnitude in this state since the screwworm.
I mean, it affects all aspects of agriculture.
And it also is affecting our
28 1 2 3 4 5 6 recreation, and the screwworm didn't even do that.
