Melinda Causey, please.
MS. CAUSEY: Good morning.
I'm Melinda Causey with Van Zyverden, Incorporated, out of Meridian,
20 21 22 23 24 25
Mississippi.
We're a wholesale distributor of flower bulbs, perennials, fruits, and vegetables.
We market our products throughout the United States, Canada, and several European countries.
We maintain a sales force to service every state in the United States, and we're the largest privately-owned bulb company in the United States, with sales exceeding over
52 1 2 3 4 5 6 $40 million.
Van Zyverden is also the largest green industry business in Mississippi, employing more than 350 individuals during the peak shipping seasons.
Our company operates under a compliance agreement with the USDA and the state of Mississippi that is accepted in all states.
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
Without a uniform quarantine, it would be impossible for us to comply with each state independently.
Inspections are routinely made of our facilities to ensure proper regulatory treatment is maintained, and all shipping cartons are properly identified with the federal and the state quarantine programs.
Efforts to eradicate the imported fire ant was
14 15 16 17 18 19
attempted for years but was never successful.
The USDA's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service has maintained a quarantine to slow the spread to the uninfested areas by regulating the various means of spreading the pest.
Nursery and greenhouse products have long been a significant focus of quarantine efforts.
The IFA quarantine
20 21 22 23 24 25
includes explicit rules for protecting, certifying, and shipping the fire-ant-free nursery and greenhouse plants.
Quarantine surveys, compliance monitoring, and enforcement responsibilities are shared by the APHIS and the IFAinfested states.
We have observed funding reduced for the IFA
53 1 2 3 4 5 6 quarantine program for years.
While operating at reduced funding, the states and the green industry was expected to do more to curb the spread of this pest.
Now there is an attempt to abolish the imported fire ant quarantine, and I believe at the expense of the thriving and growing green industry.
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
The green industry is growing rapidly and needs the continuity provided by the USDA, the APHIS, and the PP
Fortunately, the USDA plant pest quarantines are uniform from one state to the next.
Unlike the EPA pesticide laws, which vary from state to state, a state plant pest law can be no more restrictive than the federal law.
14 15 16 17 18 19
The federal quarantine does establish a framework for a coordinated, consistent approach to slowing the fire ant spread.
Without the USDA-APHIS involvement, the states will have to endure that burden alone, trying to deal with the fire ants.
Experience with several other quarantine pests
20 21 22 23 24 25
and noxious weeds has clearly demonstrated that meaningful federal participation enhances the effort.
States have varying resources and priorities, and if they are not uniform, one state's efforts is easily undermined by a neighboring state with a lax quarantine program.
Several factors associated with national commerce
54 1 2 3 4 5 6 in nursery stock, including short-interval delivery and brokerage, also contribute to a greater risk when certification and shipping regulations vary from state to state.
All this translates to a less effective effort to slow the IFA spread.
For the nursery and greenhouse industry, the
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
current quarantine effort means one set of uniform shipping rules for all types of nursery products, interstate.
This, of course, would be very valuable for our company.
Revocation of the quarantine would influence uninfested states to promulgate and enforce their own rules, adding an administrative burden to the states and leaving industries struggling to comply with confusing and possibly even
14 15 16 17 18 19
conflicting demands for treatment and certification.
Van Zyverden vigorously supports the continuation and adequate funding of the federal imported fire ant quarantine.
Thank you.
MR. LIDSKY: Thank you.
Is Martin Hubert present?
20 21 22 23 24 25
MR. HUBERT: Good morning.
My name is Martin Hubert, and as the deputy commissioner of the Texas Department of Agriculture, I'm here representing the leading plant regulatory authority in the state of Texas.
Texas ranks second in the nation in agriculture, and our nursery industry ranks third in the state in total cash receipts.
55 1 2 3 4 5 6 Activities in agricultural industries are affected by the imported fire ant quarantine actions.
We applaud the USDA-APHIS PPQ for holding these meetings and permitting affected stakeholders to comment on the course of action that the agency should take in dealing with plant protection programs that affect us all.
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
The imported fire ant is an invasive insect pest accidentally introduced into the U.S. near Mobile, Alabama, during the 1920s.
Efforts to eradicate it continued until the 1970s but were unsuccessful.
The USDA's APHIS has maintained a quarantine to slow the spread of IFA to uninfested areas as a result of human activities.
The quarantine includes across-the-states uniform
14 15 16 17 18 19
rules for the shipment of fire-ant-free nursery and greenhouse plants.
Quarantine activities such as pest surveys, compliance monitoring, and enforcement of violations are shared by APHIS and the states.
However, the APHIS budget has been declining for years, and in fiscal year 2000 has been virtually eliminated.
This poses an
20 21 22 23 24 25
undue burden on states and the affected industries, and it may result in revocation of the federal fire ant quarantine altogether.
The importance of quarantine in facilitating interstate commerce while guarding the spread of IFA to free regions requires that federal funding assistance be restored.
56 1 2 3 4 5 6 The imported fire ant has spread throughout the Southeast from North Carolina to Florida, to eastern and central Texas.
Several counties in Southern California are also partly infested.
However, large areas of the United States, including Texas, are still IFA free and they would like to stay free of this significant human health and
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
agricultural pest as long as possible.
The quarantine allows for a coordinated, consistent, and uniform approach to slowing the spread of IFA.
Without USDA-APHIS involvement, states alone will have to endure the burden of trying to deal with this pest.
Currently, the nursery and greenhouse industry regards IFA quarantine as one set of uniform rules for shipping
14 15 16 17 18 19
interstate products.
The southern states and California are major production areas for nursery and greenhouse plants, growing billions of dollars' worth of trees, shrubs, flowers, and other plants.
Many of these plants are shipped to other parts of the country.
Revocation of the quarantine would
20 21 22 23 24 25
allow uninfested states to pass their own rules, leaving industry to comply with confusing, perhaps even conflicting demands for treating and certifying plants.
This concern became a reality for the Texas beekeeping industry this past year.
Beehives certified free of IFA using the accepted Texas protocol were regulated
57 1 2 3 4 5 6 differently by Arizona and other western states, resulting in an undue burden on the beekeeping industry.
TDA has consistently adopted the federal IFA quarantine under subchapter J of the Texas Administrative Code and continues to enforce a quarantine.
National concern over invasive species is at an all-time high.
The
7 8 9 10 11 12 13
imported fire ant is an invasive species of public health and agricultural concern.
Preventing or slowing its movement to many uninfested states is a shared goal and one that we believe the federal government should share regulatory funding for.
Already the infested states pick up most of the burden in costs of surveying, certifying crops, and
14 15 16 17 18 19
enforcing the quarantine.
Regulated nurseries spend tens of thousands of dollars each year to meet the quarantine specifications.
TDA agrees with the National Plant Board's position that $7.5 million should be funded by USDA-APHIS for a shared effort that will help fund critical surveys,
20 21 22 23 24 25
compliance monitoring, and enforcement assistance.
It will help ensure that fire-ant-free nursery and agricultural products are being transported and sold in the most viable markets.
This funding should be made available beginning fiscal year 2001.
And I have a copy of my comments.
58 1 2 3 4 5 6 MR. LIDSKY: Great.
